article.headline: Thomas sparks third-quarter fun
article.linkText: Heat held to 64 points in loss to Knicks
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- The New York Knicks are coping just fine without Allan Houston. Stephon Marbury scored all 16 of his points in the first half, and the Knicks held the Miami Heat to a season-low point total in a 76-64 victory Saturday. New York extended its winning streak to four games, even though Houston missed all four because of sore knees. "We're playing well right now, we're clicking," said forward Kurt Thomas, who scored all 14 of his points in the second half. "We're waiting for Allan to get back. We know we're going to be a much stronger team when he gets back, when he's healthy." The Heat scored just 10 points in the fourth quarter, going 6:11 without a field goal. "Missing got contagious for us today," said forward Brian Grant, who returned to the lineup after missing five games. "We missed a lot of open looks. You hate when that happens in such a crucial game, and we felt that this was a crucial game for us." New York, which remained seventh in the Eastern Conference standings, took three of four from its Atlantic Division rival this season. Miami lost its third straight overall. Lamar Odom had 18 points and 14 rebounds to pace the Heat, who last led 15-14 with three minutes left in the first quarter. Miami shot 30.5 percent overall, including 1-of-15 from behind the 3-point line. The Heat's starting backcourt of Rafer Alston and Eddie Jones went a combined 7-of-26. "I'm glad we don't have to play them anymore," said Alston, who shot 3-of-10. "It's tough when you're playing a team which you're fighting for a playoff spot. You tend to think and worry about parts of the game more instead of just playing." Shandon Anderson, starting in Houston's absence, scored 12 points as the Knicks placed five players in double figures while earning their third straight road win. Thomas scored his first 10 points in the third quarter -- hitting all five shots -- as New York took a 63-54 lead. Marbury finished with eight assists. "Our choice was on pick-and-roles to trap Stephon and make him give the ball up," Miami coach Stan Van Gundy said. "Sometimes we got to Kurt quick enough, sometimes we didn't. He did a great job making shots." The Knicks shot 43 percent and led 43-36 at halftime. The Heat hit just seven of 13 free throws. "Stephon is starting to take over and run the show," said New York's Lenny Wilkens, who increased his NBA coaching record to 1,300 wins. "Kurt had a hot hand and Stephon kept getting him the ball." Marbury scored 11 points, including three 3-pointers, to help the Knicks take a 19-17 lead after one quarter. Odom had six rebounds but only one point in the period. "We have a nice balance and chemistry going," Marbury said. "When Allan comes back, that will be even better for us. "So, he can rest and get healthy. When he comes back, we're going to have much more firepower."

Game notes
Miami's Caron Butler, who shot just 2-of-9 from the field and 4-of-10 on free throws, bruised his right elbow diving for a loose ball. He will be evaluated Sunday. ... Wilkens, 8-3 as Knicks coach, has a career coaching record of 1,300-1,117. ... Grant had missed the previous five games due to sore knees and a stomach virus. Heat guard Dwyane Wade missed his second consecutive game because of a left foot sprain. ... Odom scored in double figures for a career-high 25th consecutive game. ... The Heat activated forward Rasual Butler (groin strain) from the injured list and placed center Wang Zhi-Zhi (sprained right ankle) on the injured list. ... Musician Jimmy Buffet, once thrown out of a Knicks-Heat game, sat in the front row behind the basket.
